1
00:00:02,002 --> 00:00:03,838
Miles, fancy a drink?

2
00:00:03,838 --> 00:00:05,631
I can‘t.
Keiko and the kids

3
00:00:05,631 --> 00:00:07,132
are waiting on me for dinner.

4
00:00:07,132 --> 00:00:08,843
Next Thursday--
book a holosuite.

5
00:00:08,843 --> 00:00:10,218
They‘re going to Bajor.

6
00:00:11,762 --> 00:00:12,972
Hi, Julian.

7
00:00:12,972 --> 00:00:15,223
Hi.
You going to Vic‘s?

8
00:00:15,223 --> 00:00:16,391
Yes.

9
00:00:16,391 --> 00:00:18,310
Mind if I join?

10
00:00:18,310 --> 00:00:21,229
Uh... actually, we
were looking forward

11
00:00:21,229 --> 00:00:23,357
to spending
an evening alone.

12
00:00:23,357 --> 00:00:25,108
Great.

13
00:00:25,108 --> 00:00:27,068
Well, have a great time.

14
00:00:28,863 --> 00:00:30,489
I understand.

15
00:00:41,041 --> 00:00:42,710
Cheeky virus.

16
00:00:42,710 --> 00:00:45,128
You‘ve gone and mutated on me.

17
00:00:46,463 --> 00:00:50,342
Well, you can run,
but you can‘t hide.

18
00:00:58,225 --> 00:00:59,977
Lights.

19
00:01:02,730 --> 00:01:04,773
Nog to Dr. Bashir.

20
00:01:05,607 --> 00:01:07,150
Go ahead.

21
00:01:07,150 --> 00:01:09,904
You‘re needed
in the Infirmary, sir.

22
00:01:09,904 --> 00:01:11,947
It‘s 3:00 in the morning.

23
00:01:11,947 --> 00:01:14,366
Isn‘t Dr. Girani on duty?

24
00:01:14,366 --> 00:01:15,784
Not anymore.

25
00:01:15,784 --> 00:01:17,828
Admiral Patrick threw her out.

26
00:01:18,871 --> 00:01:20,581
Admiral who?

27
00:01:20,581 --> 00:01:23,417
He wants to see you
immediately, sir.

28
00:01:23,417 --> 00:01:25,084
On my way.

29
00:01:29,381 --> 00:01:30,799
(<i> door opens</i> )

30
00:01:30,799 --> 00:01:33,092
What‘s going on, Ensign?

31
00:01:33,092 --> 00:01:34,428
Sir, Admiral Patrick
and his staff

32
00:01:34,428 --> 00:01:35,763
just arrived
on the<i> Farragut.</i>

33
00:01:35,763 --> 00:01:37,180
What happened
to Dr. Girani?

34
00:01:37,180 --> 00:01:38,432
The Admiral said
she was asking

35
00:01:38,432 --> 00:01:40,350
too many stupid
questions.

36
00:01:44,438 --> 00:01:46,273
Dr. Bashir reporting
as ordered.

37
00:01:46,273 --> 00:01:47,733
Finally.

38
00:01:48,943 --> 00:01:50,611
Patrick?!

39
00:01:50,611 --> 00:01:51,904
That‘s Admiral Patrick.

40
00:01:51,904 --> 00:01:53,739
Mind your manners,
Doctor.

41
00:01:53,739 --> 00:01:54,990
What are you
doing here?

42
00:01:54,990 --> 00:01:56,784
That‘s a stupid question.

43
00:01:56,784 --> 00:01:58,786
Where did you get
those uniforms?

44
00:01:58,786 --> 00:02:00,955
That‘s a stupid question, too.

45
00:02:00,955 --> 00:02:02,623
Please excuse
the doctor, sir.

46
00:02:02,623 --> 00:02:04,041
He just woke up.

47
00:02:04,041 --> 00:02:06,001
They‘re not
Starfleet officers, Nog.

48
00:02:06,001 --> 00:02:07,502
They‘re not?

49
00:02:07,502 --> 00:02:08,921
We‘re mutants.

50
00:02:08,921 --> 00:02:10,839
Genetically
engineered mutants.

51
00:02:10,839 --> 00:02:12,758
Can‘t you tell?

52
00:02:12,758 --> 00:02:14,593
BASHIR: Does anybody
at the Institute
know you‘re missing?

53
00:02:14,593 --> 00:02:17,429
That‘s a stupid...
Will you stop saying that!

54
00:02:17,429 --> 00:02:18,973
Why are you
so upset?

55
00:02:18,973 --> 00:02:21,100
You wanted Sarina
brought here. Well...

56
00:02:22,267 --> 00:02:23,602
here she is.

57
00:02:23,602 --> 00:02:25,562
(<i> sighs</i> )

58
00:02:25,562 --> 00:02:28,107
I was considering bringing
Sarina here for treatment

59
00:02:28,107 --> 00:02:29,900
when I was ready,

60
00:02:29,900 --> 00:02:31,819
but I still have to modify
my surgical equipment

61
00:02:31,819 --> 00:02:33,487
before I can begin
the procedure.

62
00:02:33,487 --> 00:02:35,030
Well, don‘t worry--
we‘ll help you.

63
00:02:35,030 --> 00:02:36,490
And when we‘re through
with Sarina,

64
00:02:36,490 --> 00:02:38,325
she will be just like us.

65
00:02:38,325 --> 00:02:40,577
Do you have any idea

66
00:02:40,577 --> 00:02:43,038
how much trouble you could
get into for impersonating
Starfleet officers?

67
00:02:43,038 --> 00:02:45,165
Jack, you didn‘t say
anything about us
getting into trouble.

68
00:02:45,165 --> 00:02:46,458
Well, we didn‘t get
caught, did we?

69
00:02:46,458 --> 00:02:48,209
Didn‘t anybody
question you?

70
00:02:48,209 --> 00:02:50,796
Of course. But when they did,
Patrick would say...

71
00:02:50,796 --> 00:02:52,673
That‘s a stupid...

72
00:02:52,673 --> 00:02:55,342
You‘d be surprised
how well it works.

73
00:02:55,342 --> 00:02:56,677
I‘ll say.

74
00:02:56,677 --> 00:02:58,012
What are they
going do to us?

75
00:02:58,012 --> 00:02:59,178
Oh, it‘s all right.

76
00:02:59,178 --> 00:03:00,681
I‘ll find a way

77
00:03:00,681 --> 00:03:03,642
to straighten this
out... somehow.

78
00:03:06,394 --> 00:03:08,939
Hello, Sarina.
Remember me?

79
00:03:08,939 --> 00:03:11,399
Of course
she remembers you.
She‘s not an idiot.

80
00:03:11,399 --> 00:03:13,276
She‘s just a little
cataleptic.

81
00:03:13,276 --> 00:03:16,195
Are you really
going to be able
to make her better?

82
00:03:16,195 --> 00:03:19,825
I‘m going to do
everything I can.

83
00:03:19,825 --> 00:03:21,576
I promise.

84
00:05:20,695 --> 00:05:22,614
They posed as an Admiral
and his staff.

85
00:05:22,614 --> 00:05:24,908
If you want me to convince
Starfleet not to press charges,

86
00:05:24,908 --> 00:05:27,286
you‘re going to have to give me
a damn good reason.

87
00:05:27,286 --> 00:05:29,246
They wanted
to bring Sarina here
so that I could help her.

88
00:05:29,246 --> 00:05:31,331
They meant well.
They meant well?

89
00:05:31,331 --> 00:05:33,667
That‘s the same
excuse you gave me
when they were caught

90
00:05:33,667 --> 00:05:36,170
trying to pass military
secrets to the Dominion.

91
00:05:36,170 --> 00:05:37,462
They were trying
to save lives...

92
00:05:37,462 --> 00:05:39,047
Doctor, I appreciate

93
00:05:39,047 --> 00:05:40,966
that you feel a
connection to them

94
00:05:40,966 --> 00:05:43,135
because you are genetically
engineered yourself,

95
00:05:43,135 --> 00:05:46,221
but they have displayed
a consistent disregard
for the rules

96
00:05:46,221 --> 00:05:48,307
that the rest of
society lives by.

97
00:05:48,307 --> 00:05:51,310
Maybe that‘s because
they‘re not allowed
to live in society.

98
00:05:51,310 --> 00:05:52,936
We are not here
to debate Federation policy

99
00:05:52,936 --> 00:05:54,980
toward
the genetically enhanced.

100
00:05:54,980 --> 00:05:57,232
We are here to discuss
what to do about these people

101
00:05:57,232 --> 00:05:58,775
now that they‘re aboard.

102
00:05:58,775 --> 00:06:00,777
Of course.

103
00:06:00,777 --> 00:06:02,612
Well, with your
permission, sir,

104
00:06:02,612 --> 00:06:05,448
I would like to proceed
with Sarina‘s treatment.

105
00:06:05,448 --> 00:06:08,702
I take it the Institute
has given the approval
to move forward?

106
00:06:08,702 --> 00:06:12,039
A copy of the medical
protocols I submitted.

107
00:06:12,039 --> 00:06:14,082
Dr. Loews,
Sarina‘s legal guardian,

108
00:06:14,082 --> 00:06:16,210
has given her consent.

109
00:06:16,210 --> 00:06:19,921
Well, it appears that
this procedure has never
been done before.

110
00:06:19,921 --> 00:06:21,840
Well, there‘s no guarantee
that it will work, of course,

111
00:06:21,840 --> 00:06:23,967
but if it does, it could change
everything for her.

112
00:06:23,967 --> 00:06:26,303
There‘s no reason
to think that she‘s suffering

113
00:06:26,303 --> 00:06:29,056
from the same type
of behavioral disorders
as Jack and the others.

114
00:06:29,056 --> 00:06:31,516
Her problem is that she‘s
trapped inside her own mind.

115
00:06:31,516 --> 00:06:33,476
This could free her.

116
00:06:33,476 --> 00:06:35,603
There are still a few technical
issues I have to work on,

117
00:06:35,603 --> 00:06:38,523
but I feel confident
that I can iron them all out.

118
00:06:38,523 --> 00:06:42,277
You‘ve put in a lot of time
on this, haven‘t you?

119
00:06:42,277 --> 00:06:44,071
I owe it to her, sir.

120
00:06:44,071 --> 00:06:45,947
I could have ended up
the same way as Sarina,

121
00:06:45,947 --> 00:06:48,407
but I was lucky.
My DNA re-sequencing

122
00:06:48,407 --> 00:06:51,203
didn‘t have
any unintended side effects.

123
00:06:52,746 --> 00:06:54,706
All right, Doctor.

124
00:06:54,706 --> 00:06:57,709
I‘ll take care of Starfleet.
You take care of Sarina.

125
00:06:57,709 --> 00:06:59,502
Thank you, sir.
I‘ll arrange to have

126
00:06:59,502 --> 00:07:01,713
the rest of the people
sent back to the Institute.

127
00:07:01,713 --> 00:07:04,966
Actually, I was hoping
you‘d allow them to stay
on for awhile.

128
00:07:04,966 --> 00:07:06,551
For what reason?

129
00:07:06,551 --> 00:07:08,220
Sarina‘s spent the last
15 years with them.

130
00:07:08,220 --> 00:07:09,888
Now, assuming
the procedure works

131
00:07:09,888 --> 00:07:11,932
and she comes out
of her isolation,

132
00:07:11,932 --> 00:07:14,475
I think it would be
helpful to have some
familiar faces around.

133
00:07:14,475 --> 00:07:17,396
Well, we‘ll arrange
for quarters

134
00:07:17,396 --> 00:07:18,980
to be set up in
the cargo bay.

135
00:07:18,980 --> 00:07:20,815
I appreciate it.

136
00:07:21,900 --> 00:07:24,319
Just make sure
they stay there.

137
00:07:24,319 --> 00:07:26,988
I don‘t want them to get
out and cause trouble
like they did the last time.

138
00:07:26,988 --> 00:07:28,823
I‘ll see that it
doesn‘t happen again.

139
00:07:28,823 --> 00:07:31,868
I‘ll hold you to that.
One thing more.

140
00:07:31,868 --> 00:07:33,578
Get them out
of those uniforms.

141
00:07:33,578 --> 00:07:34,871
Aye, sir.

142
00:07:36,915 --> 00:07:38,792
There. Don‘t you
look pretty?

143
00:07:38,792 --> 00:07:40,168
JACK:
Why are we doing
this anyway?

144
00:07:40,168 --> 00:07:41,378
PATRICK:
Keep going.

145
00:07:41,378 --> 00:07:42,754
JACK:
Here?

146
00:07:42,754 --> 00:07:44,672
A little to the left.

147
00:07:46,216 --> 00:07:47,968
That‘s not where
it was last time.

148
00:07:47,968 --> 00:07:49,594
Oh, what difference
does it make?

149
00:07:49,594 --> 00:07:52,264
He‘s right.
Fine.

150
00:07:52,264 --> 00:07:53,348
How‘s that?

151
00:07:53,348 --> 00:07:55,016
Much better.

152
00:07:55,016 --> 00:07:56,684
Here he is!

153
00:07:56,684 --> 00:07:58,353
Well, well, what did
the Captain say?

154
00:07:58,353 --> 00:08:00,563
All systems are a go.
See? See?

155
00:08:00,563 --> 00:08:02,399
I told you it was a good
idea to bring her here.

156
00:08:02,399 --> 00:08:03,775
That‘s right, Jack,
I remember.

157
00:08:03,775 --> 00:08:05,402
So, when do
we operate?

158
00:08:05,402 --> 00:08:06,861
We?

159
00:08:06,861 --> 00:08:08,696
You‘re going to
need some help.

160
00:08:08,696 --> 00:08:09,906
Oh, so you‘re
a surgeon now?

161
00:08:09,906 --> 00:08:11,283
How hard
can it be?

162
00:08:11,283 --> 00:08:12,993
Um, thanks
for the offer, but...

163
00:08:12,993 --> 00:08:15,412
Oh, I get it.
You want to take
all the credit.

164
00:08:15,412 --> 00:08:18,290
It‘s not about credit.
It‘s about what‘s best
for Sarina, I think.

165
00:08:18,290 --> 00:08:22,294
Fine. I‘m busy, anyway.
New project.

166
00:08:22,294 --> 00:08:24,254
Oh, glad to hear it.
What are you working on?

167
00:08:24,254 --> 00:08:27,341
Wouldn‘t you
like to know?
(<i> chuckling</i> )

168
00:08:27,341 --> 00:08:29,676
Well, I‘ll leave you to it,
but, uh, do me a favor

169
00:08:29,676 --> 00:08:32,346
and, uh, change out
of those uniforms.

170
00:08:39,186 --> 00:08:43,690
Sarina, I‘d like to take
you to the Infirmary
and run a few tests.

171
00:08:43,690 --> 00:08:45,150
Is that all right?

172
00:08:46,401 --> 00:08:48,028
She‘s afraid it‘s going to hurt.

173
00:08:48,028 --> 00:08:50,364
It won‘t hurt.
I promise.

174
00:08:50,364 --> 00:08:52,366
You‘re in good hands...

175
00:08:52,366 --> 00:08:54,409
very good hands.

176
00:08:55,660 --> 00:08:57,287
Don‘t get your
hopes up, Julian.

177
00:08:57,287 --> 00:08:59,247
It‘s over
between the two of us.

178
00:08:59,247 --> 00:09:01,708
I have a new man in my life...

179
00:09:01,708 --> 00:09:04,378
that gorgeous
little Ferengi.

180
00:09:04,378 --> 00:09:07,297
Nog?
Jealous?

181
00:09:07,297 --> 00:09:09,757
Oh, that‘s so sweet.

182
00:09:13,553 --> 00:09:15,222
Hurry back.

183
00:09:20,935 --> 00:09:23,313
BASHIR:
Sarina‘s cerebral cortex
was genetically enhanced

184
00:09:23,313 --> 00:09:27,317
in order to accelerate
the rate at which she can
process information.

185
00:09:27,317 --> 00:09:30,404
Now, the only problem is,
her visual and auditory systems

186
00:09:30,404 --> 00:09:33,114
can‘t channel the stimuli
into the cortex fast enough,

187
00:09:33,114 --> 00:09:34,949
so, because
they‘re out of sync

188
00:09:34,949 --> 00:09:37,160
she can‘t focus on
what‘s going on around her.

189
00:09:37,160 --> 00:09:39,620
Well, is there any way
to get her sensory
processors up to speed?

190
00:09:39,620 --> 00:09:43,333
I need to stimulate
the growth of new synapses
in the thalamus,

191
00:09:43,333 --> 00:09:46,503
which means...
I have to manipulate

192
00:09:46,503 --> 00:09:49,089
neural proteins
at a subatomic level.

193
00:09:49,089 --> 00:09:51,049
Well, then you‘ve
got a problem.

194
00:09:51,049 --> 00:09:54,094
This is the most advanced
neocortical probe made,

195
00:09:54,094 --> 00:09:56,012
and it‘s not nearly
that accurate.

196
00:09:56,012 --> 00:09:58,306
Now you know why
I asked you down here.

197
00:09:58,306 --> 00:09:59,807
Well, I wish I could
help you, Julian,

198
00:09:59,807 --> 00:10:01,851
but at resolutions
that small,

199
00:10:01,851 --> 00:10:04,979
quantum fluctuations are
impossible to control,

200
00:10:04,979 --> 00:10:07,190
and I can‘t make this
thing any more accurate.

201
00:10:07,190 --> 00:10:09,734
How can you say that before
you‘ve even tried it?

202
00:10:09,734 --> 00:10:13,363
I‘m sorry, Julian.
It-it-it can‘t be done.
I‘m sorry.

203
00:10:13,363 --> 00:10:15,698
Well, sorry just isn‘t
good enough, Miles.

204
00:10:15,698 --> 00:10:19,244
This is Sarina‘s
only chance at living
a normal life.

205
00:10:19,244 --> 00:10:21,788
Julian, I can‘t break
the laws of physics.

206
00:10:21,788 --> 00:10:23,331
Nobody can.

207
00:10:33,758 --> 00:10:35,802
Your friend was right.

208
00:10:35,802 --> 00:10:37,929
You can‘t break
the laws of physics.

209
00:10:40,014 --> 00:10:42,100
ALL:
But you<i> can</i> bend them.

210
00:10:42,100 --> 00:10:44,603
JACK:
We recalibrated
the imaging diodes.

211
00:10:44,603 --> 00:10:47,188
It is so accurate
that you could clip
the wings of an angel

212
00:10:47,188 --> 00:10:48,815
dancing on the
head of a pin.

213
00:10:48,815 --> 00:10:51,692
Uh... if you wanted to.

214
00:12:01,221 --> 00:12:02,889
Anything?

215
00:12:10,313 --> 00:12:12,148
(<i> sighs</i> )

216
00:12:12,148 --> 00:12:14,025
Sarina?

217
00:12:14,025 --> 00:12:16,611
Now, just how am I
supposed to know

218
00:12:16,611 --> 00:12:18,779
you understand me

219
00:12:18,779 --> 00:12:22,783
if you don‘t give
me some sign, hmm?

220
00:12:22,783 --> 00:12:24,369
Anything.

221
00:12:24,369 --> 00:12:26,745
It doesn‘t matter
how small.

222
00:12:37,965 --> 00:12:39,426
It‘s been five days now,

223
00:12:39,426 --> 00:12:40,968
and she‘s just
as unresponsive

224
00:12:40,968 --> 00:12:43,221
as she was before
the procedure.

225
00:12:43,221 --> 00:12:44,847
I know you‘re
disappointed, Julian,

226
00:12:44,847 --> 00:12:46,683
but you did everything
that you could.

227
00:12:46,683 --> 00:12:48,685
Well, it
wasn‘t enough.

228
00:12:49,894 --> 00:12:51,396
I‘m sorry.

229
00:12:51,396 --> 00:12:54,815
Obviously, you want
to punish yourself.

230
00:12:54,815 --> 00:12:56,401
Do you want help?

231
00:12:56,401 --> 00:12:58,278
Because I‘m really good
at punishing myself.

232
00:12:58,278 --> 00:13:02,407
Let‘s see...
if I were you,
I‘d be kicking myself

233
00:13:02,407 --> 00:13:04,576
for making promises
I couldn‘t keep,

234
00:13:04,576 --> 00:13:06,745
for getting
people‘s hopes up,

235
00:13:06,745 --> 00:13:09,163
for being arrogant
enough to think
that I could help Sarina,

236
00:13:09,163 --> 00:13:12,041
even though dozens
of other doctors have failed.

237
00:13:12,041 --> 00:13:13,293
Should I
keep going?

238
00:13:13,293 --> 00:13:14,835
No.

239
00:13:14,835 --> 00:13:17,255
That just about
covers it. Thanks.

240
00:13:17,255 --> 00:13:18,797
Glad I could help.

241
00:13:21,468 --> 00:13:22,719
What is it?

242
00:13:25,012 --> 00:13:27,390
I‘m not sure.

243
00:13:35,814 --> 00:13:37,942
Excuse me.

244
00:13:37,942 --> 00:13:39,444
Sarina?

245
00:13:39,444 --> 00:13:41,820
What are you
looking at?

246
00:13:41,820 --> 00:13:44,949
Every...thing.

247
00:13:52,831 --> 00:13:56,628
(<i> halting nasal monotone):</i>
<i>You... heard me.</i>

248
00:13:56,628 --> 00:13:59,631
I thought something

249
00:13:59,631 --> 00:14:01,882
and you heard it.

250
00:14:01,882 --> 00:14:03,635
