Infirmary to Dr. Bashir.
Go ahead.

411
00:22:25,178 --> 00:22:28,346
Dr. Girani is asking for
your assistance in surgery, sir.

412
00:22:28,346 --> 00:22:30,557
I‘m on my way.

413
00:22:30,557 --> 00:22:33,936
Well, looks like I‘m
going to be tied up
for the next few hours.

414
00:22:33,936 --> 00:22:35,938
What would you like
to do in the meantime?

415
00:22:35,938 --> 00:22:37,564
Would you like a
tour of the station?

416
00:22:37,564 --> 00:22:39,233
I can ask Ezri
to show you around.

417
00:22:39,233 --> 00:22:40,776
That‘s all right.

418
00:22:40,776 --> 00:22:42,653
I think I‘ll go see Jack
and the others.

419
00:22:42,653 --> 00:22:45,198
All right.
I‘ll have someone take
you to the cargo bay,

420
00:22:45,198 --> 00:22:48,075
and when I‘m finished
with surgery
I‘ll join you there.

421
00:22:48,075 --> 00:22:50,953
Oh, wait. You need
your breakfast.

422
00:22:58,711 --> 00:23:00,129
Thank you.

423
00:23:08,179 --> 00:23:10,931
The fact is, is that
the universe is going
to stop expanding,

424
00:23:10,931 --> 00:23:12,933
and it is going
to collapse in on itself.

425
00:23:12,933 --> 00:23:14,935
We‘ve got to do something
before it‘s too late.

426
00:23:14,935 --> 00:23:16,520
How much time
do we have left?

427
00:23:16,520 --> 00:23:18,189
60 trillion years--
70 at the most.

428
00:23:18,189 --> 00:23:20,149
Oh, no!

429
00:23:20,149 --> 00:23:22,318
Isn‘t Nog handsome?

430
00:23:25,863 --> 00:23:27,614
What are
you doing?!

431
00:23:27,614 --> 00:23:30,034
We are running
out of time!

432
00:23:30,034 --> 00:23:32,286
Sarina! Thank God.

433
00:23:32,286 --> 00:23:34,997
Nobody else around here
ever listens to me.

434
00:23:34,997 --> 00:23:37,250
What is it, Jack?
What‘s wrong?

435
00:23:37,250 --> 00:23:41,087
There‘s too much matter.
The universe is too heavy
for its own good.

436
00:23:41,087 --> 00:23:43,421
You need
to lighten the load.

437
00:23:43,421 --> 00:23:46,633
Yes, yes, yes, exactly.
We have to find some way
to decrease the mass.

438
00:23:46,633 --> 00:23:48,302
Of the entire
universe?

439
00:23:48,302 --> 00:23:51,264
That‘s the whole<i> point.</i>
<i>Is that possible?</i>

440
00:23:51,264 --> 00:23:53,140
That‘s what we‘re trying
to figure out, Sarina.

441
00:23:53,140 --> 00:23:56,018
What if we found a way
to manipulate subspace?

442
00:23:56,018 --> 00:23:59,397
Mmm... hmm-hmm-hmm-hmm.
Change the cosmological
constant.

443
00:23:59,397 --> 00:24:01,941
Mmm. Yes, yes, yes.
That‘d do the trick.

444
00:24:01,941 --> 00:24:05,485
You can‘t change
the cosmological constant.

445
00:24:06,904 --> 00:24:08,906
You know something,
Sarina, we are trying

446
00:24:08,906 --> 00:24:10,908
to save existence
as we know it,

447
00:24:10,908 --> 00:24:13,244
and all you can
do is criticize.

448
00:24:13,244 --> 00:24:14,620
I‘m sorry.

449
00:24:14,620 --> 00:24:16,622
Thank you!
Now, where were we?

450
00:24:16,622 --> 00:24:18,040
PATRICK:
Manipulating
subspace.

451
00:24:18,040 --> 00:24:20,334
JACK:
Right, right.

452
00:24:20,334 --> 00:24:21,919
(<i> sighs</i> )

453
00:24:35,975 --> 00:24:38,227
Doctor!

454
00:24:40,104 --> 00:24:42,731
Glad you‘re here.
Is she all right?

455
00:24:43,774 --> 00:24:45,443
Sarina, are you
all right?

456
00:24:46,319 --> 00:24:48,237
She‘s fine.

457
00:24:48,237 --> 00:24:50,906
Listen, you have to talk
to Starfleet for us.

458
00:24:50,906 --> 00:24:53,117
We need subspace
field generators-- lots of them.

459
00:24:53,117 --> 00:24:54,827
Can we talk
about it later?

460
00:24:54,827 --> 00:24:57,955
Later? There isn‘t going
to be a "later" later.

461
00:25:02,251 --> 00:25:03,794
JACK:
Now, once we get the
field generators...

462
00:25:03,794 --> 00:25:05,545
Sarina?

463
00:25:06,755 --> 00:25:08,506
Hi.

464
00:25:08,506 --> 00:25:10,468
Is something wrong?

465
00:25:10,468 --> 00:25:14,013
Oh, no. They‘re used
to my being quiet.

466
00:25:14,013 --> 00:25:15,722
It‘s easier this way.

467
00:25:18,100 --> 00:25:19,810
