I remember you.

495
00:26:45,645 --> 00:26:47,398
You‘re Julian‘s
best friend.

496
00:26:47,398 --> 00:26:50,568
Well... we get on
all right.

497
00:26:50,568 --> 00:26:52,694
For the most part.

498
00:26:52,694 --> 00:26:54,821
Why are you pretending
that it‘s not true?

499
00:26:54,821 --> 00:26:58,534
Because they‘re men,
and men have trouble
expressing their feelings.

500
00:27:00,202 --> 00:27:01,619
You don‘t.

501
00:27:01,619 --> 00:27:03,038
Oh, are you kidding?

502
00:27:03,038 --> 00:27:04,873
Odo never talks
about his feelings.

503
00:27:04,873 --> 00:27:06,750
He took your hand.

504
00:27:06,750 --> 00:27:08,668
He‘s showing you
his feelings.

505
00:27:09,795 --> 00:27:11,422
Thank you.

506
00:27:11,422 --> 00:27:13,757
Julian, why don‘t
you show everybody
how much you love me

507
00:27:13,757 --> 00:27:16,135
and order
the next round.

508
00:27:16,135 --> 00:27:17,344
(<i> chuckles</i> )

509
00:27:17,344 --> 00:27:18,512
(<i> chuckles</i> )

510
00:27:18,512 --> 00:27:19,846
Hey, Broik.

511
00:27:20,764 --> 00:27:22,391
I liked your friends--

512
00:27:22,391 --> 00:27:24,184
all of them.

513
00:27:24,184 --> 00:27:27,271
If I had to find
someone to replace Atlas

514
00:27:27,271 --> 00:27:30,316
and hold up the world,
it‘d be Miles.

515
00:27:30,316 --> 00:27:32,985
He‘d do it with
a smile, too.

516
00:27:32,985 --> 00:27:36,155
And Kira-- she never
doubts herself,

517
00:27:36,155 --> 00:27:37,823
which is what Odo
finds so fascinating,

518
00:27:37,823 --> 00:27:40,242
because he doubts
everything<i> but</i> her.

519
00:27:40,242 --> 00:27:42,369
What about Ezri?

520
00:27:42,369 --> 00:27:45,038
The day she realizes
she‘s more than just
the sum of her parts,

521
00:27:45,038 --> 00:27:46,790
she‘s really going
to be something.

522
00:27:46,790 --> 00:27:48,459
I can‘t believe
you saw all that

523
00:27:48,459 --> 00:27:50,336
after just a few
hours with them.

524
00:27:50,336 --> 00:27:52,670
I‘m going to have to start
putting on my poker face.

525
00:27:52,670 --> 00:27:55,048
Too late. You‘ve already
given yourself away.

526
00:27:55,048 --> 00:27:58,636
Is that right?
And how would you
describe me?

527
00:27:58,636 --> 00:28:00,179
Compassionate,

528
00:28:00,179 --> 00:28:01,805
brilliant,

529
00:28:01,805 --> 00:28:03,890
lonely.

530
00:28:03,890 --> 00:28:06,268
Well. Two out of
three isn‘t bad.

531
00:28:06,268 --> 00:28:07,645
Which two?

532
00:28:07,645 --> 00:28:09,687
Now, that would
be telling.

533
00:28:10,856 --> 00:28:13,609
I‘m glad you
liked my friends.

534
00:28:13,609 --> 00:28:15,819
I know they liked you.

535
00:28:15,819 --> 00:28:17,904
I felt so comfortable
around them.

536
00:28:17,904 --> 00:28:20,574
I didn‘t have to worry
that someone was going
to throw a tantrum

537
00:28:20,574 --> 00:28:22,451
or break into tears
all of a sudden.

538
00:28:22,451 --> 00:28:25,078
They only usually
do <i> that</i> at
staff meetings.

539
00:28:26,455 --> 00:28:28,207
Jack‘s always talking

540
00:28:28,207 --> 00:28:30,876
about how we‘re better
than normal people.

541
00:28:30,876 --> 00:28:33,587
He says that‘s why
they keep us locked up,

542
00:28:35,005 --> 00:28:36,465
but he‘s wrong.

543
00:28:36,465 --> 00:28:38,258
He couldn‘t get by
in the real world.

544
00:28:38,258 --> 00:28:40,553
He‘d get himself
into too much trouble.

545
00:28:40,553 --> 00:28:42,346
So would Lauren
and Patrick.

546
00:28:42,346 --> 00:28:45,391
That‘s why they belong
in the Institute.

547
00:28:45,391 --> 00:28:47,560
In fact, Doctor Loews wants
me to get them back there

548
00:28:47,560 --> 00:28:49,186
as soon as possible.

549
00:28:50,521 --> 00:28:52,356
I‘m not going
with them, am I?

550
00:28:52,356 --> 00:28:54,774
You don‘t belong there...

551
00:28:54,774 --> 00:28:56,485
not anymore.

552
00:28:57,570 --> 00:28:59,863
Do they know?
Not yet.

553
00:29:01,907 --> 00:29:03,909
They‘ve been like
a family to me

554
00:29:03,909 --> 00:29:05,619
for as long as I
can remember.

555
00:29:05,619 --> 00:29:07,913
I know how much
you care about them.

556
00:29:09,122 --> 00:29:10,832
As difficult as they
can be sometimes,

557
00:29:10,832 --> 00:29:13,001
I‘m going to miss them.

558
00:29:13,001 --> 00:29:16,422
We had our own little world,
just the four of us.

559
00:29:18,549 --> 00:29:21,093
So what‘s a genetically
enhanced girl supposed to do

560
00:29:21,093 --> 00:29:23,429
when she wakes up
from a long sleep?

561
00:29:25,013 --> 00:29:27,974
Point to one of those little
specks of light out there,

562
00:29:27,974 --> 00:29:32,187
pack a bag and go make
a life for herself?

563
00:29:32,187 --> 00:29:35,023
Why does she have to go
anywhere at all?

564
00:29:54,084 --> 00:29:56,253
Sarina isn‘t going back
to the Institute with you.

565
00:29:56,253 --> 00:29:58,213
She‘s not?
No, she‘s staying here.

566
00:29:58,213 --> 00:30:01,467
Oh, really? Huh.
How nice for you.

567
00:30:01,467 --> 00:30:03,677
I‘ve arranged for her
to have her own quarters.

568
00:30:03,677 --> 00:30:05,304
We‘re never going
to see her again.

569
00:30:05,304 --> 00:30:07,013
You have no right to
do this-- no right.

570
00:30:07,013 --> 00:30:08,474
Look, I know you‘re
going to miss her,

571
00:30:08,474 --> 00:30:10,601
but it‘s the best thing
for Sarina.

572
00:30:10,601 --> 00:30:12,227
We did not help you
so you could take
her away from us.

573
00:30:12,227 --> 00:30:14,104
Stop thinking about
yourself for a second,

574
00:30:14,104 --> 00:30:16,022
Jack, and think about her.

575
00:30:16,022 --> 00:30:17,983
Face it. She doesn‘t
belong with you anymore.

576
00:30:17,983 --> 00:30:20,110
Why? Because
we‘re not normal?

577
00:30:20,110 --> 00:30:22,154
Because we‘re crazy?
Oh, Jack.

578
00:30:22,154 --> 00:30:24,531
Couldn‘t you make us normal
like you did for Sarina

579
00:30:24,531 --> 00:30:26,074
and then we could
all stay together?

580
00:30:26,074 --> 00:30:27,534
Go on, Julian.
Tell them.

581
00:30:27,534 --> 00:30:29,161
There‘s nothing
you can do for<i> us.</i>

582
00:30:29,161 --> 00:30:30,663
We‘re too far gone.

583
00:30:31,830 --> 00:30:33,624
Ah, who wants to
be normal anyway?

584
00:30:33,624 --> 00:30:35,751
We‘re better
than they are.

585
00:30:35,751 --> 00:30:37,753
You don‘t see
any of them trying
to save the universe

586
00:30:37,753 --> 00:30:39,838
from collapsing,
do you? Hmm? Hmm?

587
00:30:39,838 --> 00:30:42,090
Let‘s get
back to work.

588
00:30:51,558 --> 00:30:54,520
Well, they took it
rather hard.

589
00:30:54,520 --> 00:30:56,062
I should go
talk to them.

590
00:30:56,062 --> 00:30:57,815
In the morning.

591
00:30:57,815 --> 00:31:00,900
Give them a little time
to get used to the idea.

592
00:31:02,402 --> 00:31:05,572
Come on. I‘ve got just
the thing to cheer you up.

593
00:31:10,202 --> 00:31:12,287
ALL:
Dabo!

594
00:31:12,287 --> 00:31:14,247
O‘BRIEN:
She‘s unbelievable.

595
00:31:14,247 --> 00:31:17,835
Tell them how
you do it. Go on!

596
00:31:17,835 --> 00:31:21,380
It has to do with a series
of binomial equations
and probability factors.

597
00:31:21,380 --> 00:31:23,590
Explain how you track
the dependent variables.

598
00:31:23,590 --> 00:31:25,843
It‘s really not
that interesting.

599
00:31:25,843 --> 00:31:27,761
ALL:
Dabo!

600
00:31:29,929 --> 00:31:33,392
Well, hasn‘t this been fun?

601
00:31:33,392 --> 00:31:35,811
Why not take a seat
and top off the evening

602
00:31:35,811 --> 00:31:38,355
with a lovely bottle
of spring wine?

603
00:31:38,355 --> 00:31:40,733
Should we?
He just wants you
to stop playing

604
00:31:40,733 --> 00:31:42,651
so he doesn‘t lose
any more money.

605
00:31:42,651 --> 00:31:47,113
Did I mention that
the wine was on the house?

606
00:31:47,113 --> 00:31:48,574
Julian, let‘s
sit down.

607
00:31:48,574 --> 00:31:49,991
But she‘s winning.

608
00:31:49,991 --> 00:31:51,785
I‘ve... played enough.

609
00:31:54,913 --> 00:31:57,040
QUARK:
This way, this way.

610
00:31:57,040 --> 00:31:59,042
Uh, excuse me, excuse me.

611
00:31:59,042 --> 00:32:00,627
Uh, uh, Ezri, over here.

612
00:32:02,796 --> 00:32:04,757
CROWD:
Dabo!

613
00:32:04,757 --> 00:32:06,842
(<i> laughter</i> )

614
00:32:06,842 --> 00:32:09,511
(<i> dishes clattering</i> )

615
00:32:13,306 --> 00:32:14,683
Sarina?

616
00:32:15,559 --> 00:32:17,728
This way.

617
00:32:17,728 --> 00:32:20,647
Julian, would you
mind if we left?

618
00:32:29,239 --> 00:32:31,032
Oh, I‘m sorry.

619
00:32:31,032 --> 00:32:32,701
I thought you were
having a good time.

620
00:32:32,701 --> 00:32:35,662
Oh, I was, but there
was so much commotion.

621
00:32:35,662 --> 00:32:38,081
Maybe I‘m just tired.

622
00:32:38,081 --> 00:32:40,250
I‘ll tell you what.
Tomorrow night,

623
00:32:40,250 --> 00:32:43,044
why don‘t we have
a nice, quiet dinner
in my quarters?

624
00:32:43,044 --> 00:32:45,297
I have a week‘s
leave coming up.

625
00:32:45,297 --> 00:32:47,299
I thought we might go
to Risa together,

626
00:32:47,299 --> 00:32:49,426
get away from all
the distractions around here,

627
00:32:49,426 --> 00:32:50,886
spend a little time alone.

628
00:32:50,886 --> 00:32:52,763
All right.

629
00:32:52,763 --> 00:32:54,514
I‘ll let you
get some rest, then.

630
00:33:11,782 --> 00:33:13,158
She‘s wonderful, Miles.

631
00:33:13,158 --> 00:33:15,494
I‘ve never met
anybody like her.

632
00:33:15,494 --> 00:33:18,121
She‘s brilliant,
sweet...

633
00:33:18,121 --> 00:33:21,291
everything‘s new to her.
Being with her
is so refreshing.

634
00:33:21,291 --> 00:33:24,336
She takes such delight
in what she‘s experiencing.

635
00:33:24,336 --> 00:33:27,547
It makes me appreciate
things I usually take
for granted.

636
00:33:27,547 --> 00:33:28,966
Like hot coffee?

637
00:33:28,966 --> 00:33:31,217
Like coffee... music...

638
00:33:31,217 --> 00:33:32,594
the way the stars shine.

639
00:33:32,594 --> 00:33:34,680
What is wrong with this thing?

640
00:33:34,680 --> 00:33:36,097
Are you listening to me?

641
00:33:36,097 --> 00:33:37,182
Yes.

642
00:33:37,182 --> 00:33:38,475
Yeah.

643
00:33:38,475 --> 00:33:41,060
Coffee, music, stars.

644
00:33:41,060 --> 00:33:42,729
Well, don‘t you have
anything to say?

645
00:33:42,729 --> 00:33:46,650
As a matter of fact,
I do, Julian.

646
00:33:46,650 --> 00:33:49,319
I haven‘t seen you like this
for a long time,

647
00:33:49,319 --> 00:33:51,613
and I‘m really happy for you,

648
00:33:51,613 --> 00:33:53,991
but don‘t you think
it‘s all happening
just a little too fast?

649
00:33:53,991 --> 00:33:57,285
Well, we‘re
genetically engineered.
We do everything fast.

650
00:33:58,495 --> 00:34:00,998
Julian, she‘s your patient.

651
00:34:00,998 --> 00:34:04,209
Not anymore.
I‘ve asked Doctor Girani
to take over her care.

652
00:34:06,545 --> 00:34:10,131
Miles, I don‘t think
you understand
what this means to me.

653
00:34:10,131 --> 00:34:12,425
All these years
I‘ve had to hide the fact

654
00:34:12,425 --> 00:34:14,553
that my DNA
had been re-sequenced.

655
00:34:14,553 --> 00:34:16,555
I listened to people talk about
the genetically engineered,

656
00:34:16,555 --> 00:34:18,223
saying they were all misfits.

657
00:34:18,223 --> 00:34:20,183
I used to fantasize
about meeting someone

658
00:34:20,183 --> 00:34:23,228
who was like me,
who could live a normal life,

659
00:34:23,228 --> 00:34:24,688
but it never happened--

660
00:34:24,688 --> 00:34:26,523
until Sarina.

661
00:34:26,523 --> 00:34:28,400
Don‘t you see?

662
00:34:28,400 --> 00:34:31,486
She‘s the woman I‘ve been
waiting for all my life.

663
00:34:34,072 --> 00:34:35,741
Well, good luck.

664
00:34:42,831 --> 00:34:44,416
Computer...

665
00:34:44,416 --> 00:34:46,251
music.

666
00:34:46,251 --> 00:34:48,503
Something... romantic.

667
00:34:48,503 --> 00:34:50,672
(<i> classical music playing</i> )

668
00:35:00,306 --> 00:35:03,309
Computer, locate Sarina Douglas.

669
00:35:03,309 --> 00:35:05,270
Sarina Douglas
is in her quarters

670
00:35:05,270 --> 00:35:11,026
on the Habitat Ring, corridor
H-6, section 27-Epsilon.

671
00:35:21,494 --> 00:35:23,496
Sarina!

672
00:35:23,496 --> 00:35:25,040
It‘s me.

673
00:35:27,626 --> 00:35:29,544
Computer, override door locks.

674
00:35:29,544 --> 00:35:32,380
Authorization:
Bashir-delta-five-seven-alpha.

675
00:35:32,380 --> 00:35:34,340
(<i> beeping</i> )

676
00:35:44,183 --> 00:35:46,853
I‘ve been waiting
in my quarters for you.

677
00:35:48,438 --> 00:35:49,731
Sarina?

678
00:35:57,405 --> 00:35:59,032
Is something wrong?

679
00:36:03,954 --> 00:36:05,497
Sarina.

680
00:36:16,800 --> 00:36:20,137
Apparently, the thalamic
pathways I generated
are still functioning,

681
00:36:20,137 --> 00:36:23,056
but Dr. Girani‘s not detected
any neural activity in them.

682
00:36:23,056 --> 00:36:26,018
Do you have any idea
what‘s wrong?
Not a clue.

683
00:36:26,018 --> 00:36:27,644
It‘s as if she were
just slipping away

684
00:36:27,644 --> 00:36:29,146
and there‘s
nothing I can do

685
00:36:29,146 --> 00:36:30,897
but wait and hope
she pulls out of it.

686
00:36:30,897 --> 00:36:32,482
GIRANI:
You can go in now.

687
00:36:35,986 --> 00:36:37,445
Sarina?

688
00:36:38,905 --> 00:36:41,282
Don‘t be afraid.

689
00:36:41,282 --> 00:36:44,202
Everything‘s going
to be all right.

690
00:36:46,245 --> 00:36:49,791
I‘m not going
to give up on you... ever.

691
00:37:11,312 --> 00:37:13,314
BASHIR: I don‘t know
what‘s wrong with her.

692
00:37:13,314 --> 00:37:15,400
I need your help.
Why should we help you?

693
00:37:15,400 --> 00:37:17,110
You just want to steal
her away from us.

694
00:37:17,110 --> 00:37:19,571
Look at her!
Do you really want her

695
00:37:19,571 --> 00:37:22,281
to spend the rest
of her life like this?

696
00:37:22,281 --> 00:37:24,034
I mean, I‘ve been
trying to find a way

697
00:37:24,034 --> 00:37:25,660
to reach her, but I can‘t.

698
00:37:25,660 --> 00:37:27,746
Maybe there isn‘t one.

699
00:37:27,746 --> 00:37:31,457
All I‘m asking
is that you try.

700
00:37:31,457 --> 00:37:32,918
The three of
you know her

701
00:37:32,918 --> 00:37:34,627
better than
anyone else.

702
00:37:34,627 --> 00:37:38,757
Please... I don‘t
want to lose her.

703
00:37:41,843 --> 00:37:44,763
All right, Julian.
Leave her here with us
for a while.

704
00:37:44,763 --> 00:37:46,806
We‘ll see what we can do.

705
00:37:46,806 --> 00:37:48,767
Thank you.

706
00:38:19,798 --> 00:38:22,217
Are you sure?
I‘m sure.

707
00:38:22,217 --> 00:38:23,843
We have to tell him.

708
00:38:23,843 --> 00:38:26,554
Why? This way, we can
all stay together.

709
00:38:28,514 --> 00:38:30,142
Let‘s go.

710
00:38:42,320 --> 00:38:44,322
This way.
That way.

711
00:38:44,322 --> 00:38:45,615
I think
we passed it.

712
00:38:45,615 --> 00:38:47,033
Can I help you?

713
00:38:48,409 --> 00:38:50,829
That‘s a stupid question.

714
00:38:59,254 --> 00:39:01,089
(<i> door chimes</i> )

715
00:39:02,423 --> 00:39:03,883
Come in.

716
00:39:05,218 --> 00:39:06,803
We have to talk to you.

717
00:39:06,803 --> 00:39:08,554
About Sarina?

718
00:39:08,554 --> 00:39:11,016
Tell him.

719
00:39:11,016 --> 00:39:14,352
She can still talk.
It‘s just that
she‘s afraid to.

720
00:39:14,352 --> 00:39:16,688
I don‘t understand.
What is she afraid of?

721
00:39:16,688 --> 00:39:19,983
We don‘t know.
But we think it has
something to do with you.

722
00:39:21,359 --> 00:39:22,694
I‘m going to talk to her.

723
00:39:22,694 --> 00:39:24,362
Stay here.

724
00:39:29,075 --> 00:39:30,869
BASHIR:
Sarina.

725
00:39:32,620 --> 00:39:34,622
Talk to me...

726
00:39:34,622 --> 00:39:36,624
please.

727
00:39:38,501 --> 00:39:40,837
I know you can.

728
00:39:45,800 --> 00:39:47,635
What‘s wrong?

729
00:39:51,306 --> 00:39:53,474
Is it me?

730
00:39:53,474 --> 00:39:56,228
If it is, don‘t be afraid.

731
00:39:56,228 --> 00:39:58,646
I‘m going to do
whatever it takes

732
00:39:58,646 --> 00:40:00,648
to make it right...

733
00:40:00,648 --> 00:40:02,901
because I love you.

734
00:40:05,444 --> 00:40:07,906
I want us to be together.

735
00:40:10,325 --> 00:40:12,035
Tell me.

736
00:40:14,329 --> 00:40:16,289
Do you love me?

737
00:40:19,709 --> 00:40:22,003
I don‘t know.

738
00:40:23,296 --> 00:40:27,425
I don‘t even understand
what love is.

739
00:40:27,425 --> 00:40:29,261
I don‘t understand
anything.

740
00:40:29,261 --> 00:40:30,970
Sarina...
What am I supposed to do?

741
00:40:30,970 --> 00:40:34,015
What am I supposed
to feel? Tell me.

742
00:40:34,015 --> 00:40:36,059
I want to make you happy.
I owe you everything.

743
00:40:36,059 --> 00:40:39,104
Shh. You don‘t owe me.

744
00:40:40,230 --> 00:40:42,399
You don‘t owe me anything.

745
00:40:44,650 --> 00:40:46,903
I‘m sorry.

746
00:40:46,903 --> 00:40:49,488
I wish I could be the woman
you want me to be.

747
00:40:49,488 --> 00:40:50,782
Shh.

748
00:41:10,718 --> 00:41:12,011
Morning.

749
00:41:13,263 --> 00:41:14,973
Is she gone?

750
00:41:14,973 --> 00:41:16,975
Her shuttle leaves
in a few minutes.

751
00:41:16,975 --> 00:41:18,559
What about the others?

752
00:41:18,559 --> 00:41:21,396
They left for the Institute
this morning.

753
00:41:24,649 --> 00:41:26,985
I understand you‘ve arranged
a position for Sarina

754
00:41:26,985 --> 00:41:29,446
at the Corgal
Research Center.

755
00:41:29,446 --> 00:41:31,281
Yeah, an internship.

756
00:41:31,281 --> 00:41:33,783
She‘s going to work
under one of
the scientists there,

757
00:41:33,783 --> 00:41:35,910
live with his family.

758
00:41:37,536 --> 00:41:38,913
Are you okay?

759
00:41:41,124 --> 00:41:43,918
How could I have been so blind?

760
00:41:43,918 --> 00:41:47,422
What was I thinking,
trying to move things
along so fast?

761
00:41:47,422 --> 00:41:49,882
She needed time.
I didn‘t give it to her.

762
00:41:49,882 --> 00:41:54,095
I came this close
to driving her back
inside herself.

763
00:41:54,095 --> 00:41:55,930
I‘m supposed to be a doctor.

764
00:41:55,930 --> 00:41:58,975
I‘m supposed to put
my patient‘s needs above my own.

765
00:41:58,975 --> 00:42:01,727
You didn‘t want
to be lonely anymore.

766
00:42:01,727 --> 00:42:03,271
Nobody does.

767
00:42:05,231 --> 00:42:07,275
(<i> sighs</i> )

768
00:42:08,734 --> 00:42:10,569
I have to go to work.

769
00:42:12,030 --> 00:42:14,240
You want to come over
for dinner tonight?

770
00:42:14,240 --> 00:42:16,368
Keiko‘s making tempura.

771
00:42:17,452 --> 00:42:19,996
(<i> sighs</i> ):
No, thanks.

772
00:42:45,188 --> 00:42:48,400
So here you are...
on your way

773
00:42:48,400 --> 00:42:51,777
to one of those tiny little
specks of light out there.

774
00:42:53,279 --> 00:42:55,490
I guess that‘s what
a genetically enhanced girl

775
00:42:55,490 --> 00:42:58,493
should do when she wakes up
from her sleep--

776
00:42:58,493 --> 00:43:01,162
go make a life for herself.

777
00:43:06,501 --> 00:43:07,919
I‘m going to miss you.

778
00:43:07,919 --> 00:43:10,838
I‘m going to miss you.

779
00:43:11,797 --> 00:43:13,258
You won‘t forget me?

780
00:43:13,258 --> 00:43:15,552
Forget you?

781
00:43:15,552 --> 00:43:16,928
Never.

782
00:43:16,928 --> 00:43:19,764
COMPUTER:
Final boarding call.

783
00:43:20,848 --> 00:43:23,518
Well, I‘d better go.
